    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Women, the Court and Our Votes</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Jim Hillhouse letter on May 16 editorial urges proponents of stronger laws protecting women to work for their passage at state level</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Violence Against the Constitution'' (editorial, May 16): It is true  that many states do not take seriously enough the issue of punishing those who commit violent acts against women. Yet Congress should not be automatically viewed as the savior of every poorly addressed ill in the country. Such a view too easily allows states to avoid acting responsibly in protecting their residents.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Violence Against the Constitution'' (editorial, May 16): It is true  that many states do not take seriously enough the issue of punishing those who commit violent acts against women. Yet Congress should not be automatically viewed as the savior of every poorly addressed ill in the country. Such a view too easily allows states to avoid acting responsibly in protecting their residents.</p>
        <p>It is now time for proponents of stronger laws protecting women to stop bemoaning the Supreme Court's action and get to the capitols of those states that need stronger anti-violence laws and start working with legislators, governors and local activists. The evidence compiled by Congress in its efforts to pass the Violence Against Women Act would be a good place to start for this campaign. This is what is entailed in a republican form of government.</p>
        <p>JIM HILLHOUSE  Austin, Tex., May 17, 2000</p>
      </block>
